I think a lot about the fact that the Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to also see them critically.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective consciousness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to wonder where they came from, because that was not that easy to determine back then.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we put them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong nostalgia.
As "The Office" was still on, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
That was completely different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches when they feel like it, and posts on social media with "spoiler warnings" or discusses them in private groups.
Unconsciously, we yearn for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch series like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman" like crazy, where so many one-liners appeared that would be memes today.
We brought these catchphrases along and assumed that most people already understood them.
Today one can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads massively virally.
There's too much, and there's no way to systematize it. Will we ever get out of this oversaturation?
We're trapped in a vicious cycle, constantly discovering new content, only to find out that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
That's why we need to hold onto our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works we liked can also make big mistakes.
We approach parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We're aware that it's difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes along the way.
Since we've lost the collective consciousness regarding media, we've developed a class consciousness that promotes critical thinking.
There are still those among us who put someone on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall.
We're in a phase of transformation, and I'm curious to see what the end result will be.
